-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- HEBREWS CHAPTER 12 — The Race of Faith, Divine Discipline, Mount Zion
-- 29 verses · Greek text · Word studies · Cross-refs
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- Step 1: Insert chapter metadata
INSERT INTO chapters (book_id, chapter_number, overview, theme, key_word_original, key_word_meaning, outline)
SELECT b.id, 12,
  'Hebrews 12 is the climactic exhortation of the epistle, drawing practical conclusions from the great cloud of witnesses in chapter 11. The chapter opens with the famous athletic metaphor: believers are to ''run with patience the race that is set before us, looking unto Jesus the author and finisher of our faith'' (vv.1-2). Christ endured the cross, despised the shame, and sat down at the right hand of God — He is both the pioneer and perfecter of faith. The chapter then moves to the theme of divine discipline (vv.3-11): God chastens those He loves, just as a father disciplines his children. ''No chastening for the present seemeth to be joyous, but grievous: nevertheless afterward it yieldeth the peaceable fruit of righteousness'' (v.11). Practical exhortations follow: ''lift up the hands which hang down'' (v.12), ''make straight paths for your feet'' (v.13), ''follow peace with all men, and holiness, without which no man shall see the Lord'' (v.14). The warning of Esau — who sold his birthright and found ''no place of repentance'' (v.17) — reinforces the danger of despising spiritual privilege. The chapter then unveils the magnificent contrast between Mount Sinai and Mount Zion (vv.18-24): believers have not come to the terrifying mountain of fire, darkness, and tempest (the old covenant), but to ''mount Sion, and unto the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem, and to an innumerable company of angels, to the general assembly and church of the firstborn'' (vv.22-23). The fifth and final warning passage (vv.25-29) closes the chapter: ''See that ye refuse not him that speaketh'' — for if Israel could not escape when they refused the voice at Sinai, ''much more shall not we escape, if we turn away from him that speaketh from heaven'' (v.25). God will shake both heaven and earth one final time, removing the temporal so that ''those things which cannot be shaken may remain'' (v.27). The chapter ends with a call to gratitude and reverent worship: ''for our God is a consuming fire'' (v.29).',
  'The Race of Faith, Divine Discipline, and the Unshakeable Kingdom',
  'τρέχωμεν (trechōmen)',
  'Let us run — from trechō (G5143), to run, to exert effort, to press forward in a race. The athletic imagery of the stadium permeates the chapter opening: believers are runners in a cosmic arena, surrounded by the witnesses of chapter 11, who have already finished their race. The command is present subjunctive — continuous running, not a sprint but an endurance race. Combined with ''patience'' (hypomonē — patient endurance, steadfast perseverance), the picture is of marathon faith.',
  '["The Race of Faith and Looking to Jesus (vv.1-4): Wherefore seeing we also are compassed about with so great a cloud of witnesses let us lay aside every weight and the sin which doth so easily beset us and let us run with patience the race that is set before us looking unto Jesus the author and finisher of our faith who for the joy that was set before him endured the cross despising the shame and is set down at the right hand of the throne of God; for consider him that endured such contradiction of sinners against himself lest ye be wearied and faint in your minds; ye have not yet resisted unto blood striving against sin","Divine Discipline as a Father''s Love (vv.5-11): And ye have forgotten the exhortation which speaketh unto you as unto children My son despise not thou the chastening of the Lord nor faint when thou art rebuked of him for whom the Lord loveth he chasteneth and scourgeth every son whom he receiveth; if ye endure chastening God dealeth with you as with sons; now no chastening for the present seemeth to be joyous but grievous nevertheless afterward it yieldeth the peaceable fruit of righteousness unto them which are exercised thereby","Practical Exhortations and Warning of Esau (vv.12-17): Wherefore lift up the hands which hang down and the feeble knees and make straight paths for your feet lest that which is lame be turned out of the way but let it rather be healed; follow peace with all men and holiness without which no man shall see the Lord; looking diligently lest any man fail of the grace of God lest any root of bitterness springing up trouble you and thereby many be defiled; lest there be any fornicator or profane person as Esau who for one morsel of meat sold his birthright; for ye know how that afterward when he would have inherited the blessing he was rejected for he found no place of repentance though he sought it carefully with tears","Mount Sinai versus Mount Zion (vv.18-24): For ye are not come unto the mount that might be touched and that burned with fire nor unto blackness and darkness and tempest and the sound of a trumpet and the voice of words which voice they that heard intreated that the word should not be spoken to them any more; and so terrible was the sight that Moses said I exceedingly fear and quake; but ye are come unto mount Sion and unto the city of the living God the heavenly Jerusalem and to an innumerable company of angels to the general assembly and church of the firstborn which are written in heaven and to God the Judge of all and to the spirits of just men made perfect and to Jesus the mediator of the new covenant and to the blood of sprinkling that speaketh better things than that of Abel","The Fifth Warning: The Unshakeable Kingdom (vv.25-29): See that ye refuse not him that speaketh for if they escaped not who refused him that spake on earth much more shall not we escape if we turn away from him that speaketh from heaven; whose voice then shook the earth but now he hath promised saying Yet once more I shake not the earth only but also heaven; and this word Yet once more signifieth the removing of those things that are shaken as of things that are made that those things which cannot be shaken may remain; wherefore we receiving a kingdom which cannot be moved let us have grace whereby we may serve God acceptably with reverence and godly fear for our God is a consuming fire"]'
FROM books b WHERE b.name = 'Hebrews';

-- Step 2: Insert all 29 verses (key verses with study/doctrinal notes)
INSERT INTO verses (chapter_id, verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
SELECT c.id, v.verse_number, v.kjv_text, v.original_text, v.transliteration, v.study_note, v.doctrinal_note
FROM chapters c
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'Wherefore seeing we also are compassed about with so great a cloud of witnesses, let us lay aside every weight, and the sin which doth so easily beset us, and let us run with patience the race that is set before us,',
   'τοιγαροῦν καὶ ἡμεῖς τοσοῦτον ἔχοντες περικείμενον ἡμῖν νέφος μαρτύρων ὄγκον ἀποθέμενοι πάντα καὶ τὴν εὐπερίστατον ἁμαρτίαν δι᾽ ὑπομονῆς τρέχωμεν τὸν προκείμενον ἡμῖν ἀγῶνα',
   'toigaroun kai hēmeis tosouton echontes perikeimenon hēmin nephos martyrōn onkon apothemenoi panta kai tēn euperistaton hamartian di hypomonēs trechōmen ton prokeimenon hēmin agōna',
   '''Cloud of witnesses'' (nephos martyrōn — a vast mass of witnesses like a cloud filling a stadium). These are the chapter 11 heroes who have finished their race and now surround the arena. ''Lay aside every weight'' (onkon apothemenoi — put off every encumbrance; athletes stripped off excess clothing). ''The sin which doth so easily beset us'' (tēn euperistaton hamartian — the sin that easily entangles, wraps around, clings closely). ''Run with patience'' (di hypomonēs trechōmen — through patient endurance let us keep running). The ''race'' (agōna — a contest, struggle, from which we get ''agony'') is set before us (prokeimenon — laid out, prescribed).',
   'The Christian life is framed as an athletic contest in a cosmic arena. Two actions are required before running: (1) lay aside every weight — not just sin but anything that hinders progress; (2) put off the entangling sin. The race requires hypomonē — not speed but endurance. The witnesses are not passive spectators but active testifiers whose faithful lives bear witness to the faithfulness of God.'),
  (2, 'Looking unto Jesus the author and finisher of our faith; who for the joy that was set before him endured the cross, despising the shame, and is set down at the right hand of the throne of God.',
   'ἀφορῶντες εἰς τὸν τῆς πίστεως ἀρχηγὸν καὶ τελειωτὴν Ἰησοῦν ὃς ἀντὶ τῆς προκειμένης αὐτῷ χαρᾶς ὑπέμεινεν σταυρὸν αἰσχύνης καταφρονήσας ἐν δεξιᾷ τε τοῦ θρόνου τοῦ θεοῦ κεκάθικεν',
   'aphorontes eis ton tēs pisteōs archēgon kai teleiōtēn Iēsoun hos anti tēs prokeimentēs autō charas hypemeinen stauron aischynēs kataphronēsas en dexia te tou thronou tou theou kekathiken',
   '''Looking unto Jesus'' (aphorontes eis — looking away from everything else, fixing the gaze on Jesus alone). ''Author and finisher'' (archēgon kai teleiōtēn — pioneer/originator and perfecter/completer). Jesus is the archēgos (the one who goes first, the trail-blazer) and the teleiōtēs (the one who brings to completion — a word found only here in the NT). ''For the joy set before him'' (anti tēs prokeimentēs charas — in exchange for the joy lying ahead) — Christ endured the cross because He could see the joy beyond it. ''Despising the shame'' (aischynēs kataphronēsas — thinking nothing of the disgrace). He now sits enthroned (kekathiken — perfect tense: He sat down and remains seated).',
   'Jesus is the supreme example of faith — not merely one more name in the chapter 11 list but the originator and perfecter of the entire faith enterprise. He ran His race first. The joy set before Him was the redemption of His people and His return to the Father''s glory. His enthronement at God''s right hand is the finish line that proves the race can be completed. Every believer''s faith finds its source and completion in Him.'),
  (3, 'For consider him that endured such contradiction of sinners against himself, lest ye be wearied and faint in your minds.',
   'ἀναλογίσασθε γὰρ τὸν τοιαύτην ὑπομεμενηκότα ὑπὸ τῶν ἁμαρτωλῶν εἰς αὐτὸν ἀντιλογίαν ἵνα μὴ κάμητε ταῖς ψυχαῖς ὑμῶν ἐκλυόμενοι',
   'analogisasthe gar ton toiautēn hypomemenēkota hypo tōn hamartōlōn eis auton antilogian hina mē kamēte tais psychais hymōn eklyomenoi',
   '''Consider'' (analogisasthe — reckon up, compare, calculate carefully; a mathematical term meaning to weigh the proportions). ''Endured such contradiction'' (hypomemenēkota antilogian — He bore the hostility/opposition of sinners). ''Lest ye be wearied and faint'' (hina mē kamēte eklyomenoi — lest you grow weary and collapse in your souls). The remedy for spiritual fatigue is careful contemplation of Christ''s endurance.',
   NULL),
  (4, 'Ye have not yet resisted unto blood, striving against sin.',
   'οὔπω μέχρις αἵματος ἀντικατέστητε πρὸς τὴν ἁμαρτίαν ἀνταγωνιζόμενοι',
   'oupō mechris haimatos antikatestēte pros tēn hamartian antagōnizomenoi',
   '''Not yet unto blood'' (oupō mechris haimatos — not yet to the point of blood, i.e., martyrdom). ''Striving against sin'' (antagōnizomenoi — contending against, wrestling in the contest; the word is related to agōn from v.1). The readers had suffered (10:32-34) but had not yet been martyred for their faith. Christ had resisted unto blood; they had not. The comparison both encourages (your struggle has not yet reached its ultimate test) and challenges (are you willing to go that far?).',
   NULL),
  (5, 'And ye have forgotten the exhortation which speaketh unto you as unto children, My son, despise not thou the chastening of the Lord, nor faint when thou art rebuked of him:',
   'καὶ ἐκλέλησθε τῆς παρακλήσεως ἥτις ὑμῖν ὡς υἱοῖς διαλέγεται Υἱέ μου μὴ ὀλιγώρει παιδείας κυρίου μηδὲ ἐκλύου ὑπ᾽ αὐτοῦ ἐλεγχόμενος',
   'kai eklēlēsthe tēs paraklēseōs hētis hymin hōs huiois dialegetai Huie mou mē oligōrei paideias kyriou mēde eklyou hyp autou elenchomenos',
   'Quotes Proverbs 3:11-12 (LXX). ''Ye have forgotten'' (eklēlēsthe — you have completely forgotten). ''Chastening'' (paideias — from paideia, training, education, discipline; the same root as pais/child). God''s discipline is educational, not punitive. Two wrong responses: ''despise not'' (mē oligōrei — do not think lightly of, do not disregard) and ''nor faint'' (mēde eklyou — do not collapse, do not give up). Neither ignoring discipline nor being crushed by it is appropriate.',
   NULL),
  (6, 'For whom the Lord loveth he chasteneth, and scourgeth every son whom he receiveth.',
   'ὃν γὰρ ἀγαπᾷ κύριος παιδεύει μαστιγοῖ δὲ πάντα υἱὸν ὃν παραδέχεται',
   'hon gar agapa kyrios paideuei mastigoi de panta huion hon paradechetai',
   'Continues quoting Proverbs 3:12. ''Whom the Lord loveth he chasteneth'' (hon agapa kyrios paideuei — the one the Lord loves He disciplines). Love is the motive for discipline. ''Scourgeth'' (mastigoi — whips, scourges; a stronger word than paideuei, indicating that God''s discipline can be severe). ''Every son whom he receiveth'' (panta huion hon paradechetai — every son He acknowledges/welcomes). Universality: every true son experiences discipline; its absence would indicate illegitimacy (v.8).',
   'Divine discipline is a proof of sonship, not a sign of rejection. God''s chastening flows from His love (agapē), not His wrath. The father-son relationship governs the entire passage: discipline is what fathers do for children they love. This is the primary lens through which believers should interpret suffering and hardship in their lives.'),
  (7, 'If ye endure chastening, God dealeth with you as with sons; for what son is he whom the father chasteneth not?',
   'εἰ παιδείαν ὑπομένετε ὡς υἱοῖς ὑμῖν προσφέρεται ὁ θεός τίς γάρ ἐστιν υἱὸς ὃν οὐ παιδεύει πατήρ',
   'ei paideian hypomenete hōs huiois hymin prospheretai ho theos tis gar estin huios hon ou paideuei patēr',
   '''If ye endure chastening'' (ei paideian hypomenete — if you bear up under discipline). ''God dealeth with you as with sons'' (hōs huiois hymin prospheretai ho theos — God is treating you as sons). The logic is inescapable: discipline proves sonship. The rhetorical question (''what son is he whom the father chasteneth not?'') expects the answer: none. Every legitimate son is disciplined.',
   NULL),
  (8, 'But if ye be without chastisement, whereof all are partakers, then are ye bastards, and not sons.',
   'εἰ δὲ χωρίς ἐστε παιδείας ἧς μέτοχοι γεγόνασιν πάντες ἄρα νόθοι ἐστὲ καὶ οὐχ υἱοί',
   'ei de chōris este paideias hēs metochoi gegonasin pantes ara nothoi este kai ouch huioi',
   '''Without chastisement'' (chōris paideias — apart from discipline). ''All are partakers'' (metochoi gegonasin pantes — all have become sharers in it). ''Bastards'' (nothoi — illegitimate children, born outside the family). The argument reaches its sharpest point: absence of discipline does not mean God''s favor; it means the absence of a father-son relationship. This is counter-intuitive but theologically profound.',
   NULL),
  (9, 'Furthermore we have had fathers of our flesh which corrected us, and we gave them reverence: shall we not much rather be in subjection unto the Father of spirits, and live?',
   'εἶτα τοὺς μὲν τῆς σαρκὸς ἡμῶν πατέρας εἴχομεν παιδευτὰς καὶ ἐνετρεπόμεθα οὐ πολλῷ μᾶλλον ὑποταγησόμεθα τῷ πατρὶ τῶν πνευμάτων καὶ ζήσομεν',
   'eita tous men tēs sarkos hēmōn pateras eichomen paideutos kai enetrepometha ou pollō mallon hypotagēsometha tō patri tōn pneumatōn kai zēsomen',
   'An a fortiori argument (lesser to greater): if we respected earthly fathers who disciplined us, ''much rather'' (pollō mallon — by how much more) should we submit to ''the Father of spirits'' (tō patri tōn pneumatōn — the Father of our spirits, the Creator of the spiritual realm). ''And live'' (kai zēsomen — and we shall live) — submission to God''s discipline leads to spiritual life and vitality.',
   NULL),
  (10, 'For they verily for a few days chastened us after their own pleasure; but he for our profit, that we might be partakers of his holiness.',
   'οἱ μὲν γὰρ πρὸς ὀλίγας ἡμέρας κατὰ τὸ δοκοῦν αὐτοῖς ἐπαίδευον ὁ δὲ ἐπὶ τὸ συμφέρον εἰς τὸ μεταλαβεῖν τῆς ἁγιότητος αὐτοῦ',
   'hoi men gar pros oligas hēmeras kata to dokoun autois epaideuon ho de epi to sympheron eis to metalabein tēs hagiotētos autou',
   'The contrast between human and divine discipline: earthly fathers discipline ''for a few days'' (pros oligas hēmeras — for a short time) and ''after their own pleasure'' (kata to dokoun autois — as it seemed good to them, sometimes imperfectly). But God disciplines ''for our profit'' (epi to sympheron — for our advantage, for what is beneficial). The ultimate goal: ''that we might be partakers of his holiness'' (eis to metalabein tēs hagiotētos autou — to share in His holiness). God''s discipline is always purposeful, always beneficial, always aimed at conforming us to His character.',
   'The purpose of divine discipline is theosis in the Protestant sense — not becoming God but sharing in His moral character. Holiness (hagiotes) is the goal of all God''s dealings with His children. Suffering, rightly received, produces Christlikeness.'),
  (11, 'Now no chastening for the present seemeth to be joyous, but grievous: nevertheless afterward it yieldeth the peaceable fruit of righteousness unto them which are exercised thereby.',
   'πᾶσα δὲ παιδεία πρὸς μὲν τὸ παρὸν οὐ δοκεῖ χαρᾶς εἶναι ἀλλὰ λύπης ὕστερον δὲ καρπὸν εἰρηνικὸν τοῖς δι᾽ αὐτῆς γεγυμνασμένοις ἀποδίδωσιν δικαιοσύνης',
   'pasa de paideia pros men to paron ou dokei charas einai alla lypēs hysteron de karpon eirēnikon tois di autēs gegymnesmenois apodidōsin dikaiosynēs',
   '''No chastening for the present seemeth joyous'' — honest acknowledgment that discipline is painful. ''But grievous'' (alla lypēs — but of grief/sorrow). ''Nevertheless afterward'' (hysteron de — but later). The key phrase: ''the peaceable fruit of righteousness'' (karpon eirēnikon dikaiosynēs — the peaceful harvest of righteousness). ''Exercised thereby'' (gegymnesmenois — trained, from gymnazō = to train in a gymnasium; the athletic metaphor returns). Discipline is spiritual training that produces the harvest of righteousness and peace.',
   'The agricultural metaphor complements the athletic: discipline is training (gymnasium) that yields fruit (harvest). The ''peaceable fruit of righteousness'' combines two outcomes: righteousness (right character) and peace (inner wholeness). Both are future — ''afterward'' — requiring patience and endurance. The sequence is clear: discipline → patient training → righteous character → inner peace.'),
  (12, 'Wherefore lift up the hands which hang down, and the feeble knees;',
   'διὸ τὰς παρειμένας χεῖρας καὶ τὰ παραλελυμένα γόνατα ἀνορθώσατε',
   'dio tas pareimenas cheiras kai ta paralelymena gonata anorthōsate',
   'Echoes Isaiah 35:3. ''Lift up'' (anorthōsate — strengthen, make straight again, restore). ''Hands which hang down'' (pareimenas cheiras — drooping, relaxed, listless hands). ''Feeble knees'' (paralelymena gonata — paralyzed, weakened knees). The imagery is of an exhausted runner whose arms have dropped and knees have buckled. The exhortation is to straighten up and keep going — not to start over but to continue the race.',
   NULL),
  (13, 'And make straight paths for your feet, lest that which is lame be turned out of the way; but let it rather be healed.',
   'καὶ τροχιὰς ὀρθὰς ποιήσατε τοῖς ποσὶν ὑμῶν ἵνα μὴ τὸ χωλὸν ἐκτραπῇ ἰαθῇ δὲ μᾶλλον',
   'kai trochias orthas poiēsate tois posin hymōn hina mē to chōlon ektrapē iathē de mallon',
   'Echoes Proverbs 4:26. ''Straight paths'' (trochias orthas — level tracks, smooth courses). ''Lest that which is lame be turned out of the way'' (hina mē to chōlon ektrapē — lest the limping one be dislocated/wrenched out of joint). ''But let it rather be healed'' (iathē de mallon — but rather let it be healed). The concern is corporate: the strong should create clear, smooth paths so that weaker members are not further injured. The goal is healing, not exclusion.',
   NULL),
  (14, 'Follow peace with all men, and holiness, without which no man shall see the Lord:',
   'εἰρήνην διώκετε μετὰ πάντων καὶ τὸν ἁγιασμόν οὗ χωρὶς οὐδεὶς ὄψεται τὸν κύριον',
   'eirēnēn diōkete meta pantōn kai ton hagiasmon hou chōris oudeis opsetai ton kyrion',
   '''Follow'' (diōkete — pursue, chase after, hunt down; an active, aggressive verb). Two pursuits: (1) ''peace with all men'' (eirēnēn meta pantōn — peaceful relationships with everyone); (2) ''holiness'' (ton hagiasmon — sanctification, the process of being set apart). ''Without which no man shall see the Lord'' (hou chōris oudeis opsetai ton kyrion — apart from which no one will see the Lord). Holiness is not optional but essential for the vision of God. This does not teach sinless perfection but that the direction of life must be toward holiness.',
   'Holiness (hagiasmos) is here presented as the indispensable condition for seeing God. This echoes the Beatitude ''Blessed are the pure in heart: for they shall see God'' (Matt 5:8). The pursuit of holiness is both a present activity (progressive sanctification) and a future goal (glorification). Without this pursuit — without the reality of sanctification working in a believer''s life — there is no assurance of final salvation.'),
  (15, 'Looking diligently lest any man fail of the grace of God; lest any root of bitterness springing up trouble you, and thereby many be defiled;',
   'ἐπισκοποῦντες μή τις ὑστερῶν ἀπὸ τῆς χάριτος τοῦ θεοῦ μή τις ῥίζα πικρίας ἄνω φύουσα ἐνοχλῇ καὶ διὰ ταύτης μιανθῶσιν πολλοί',
   'episkopountes mē tis hysterōn apo tēs charitos tou theou mē tis rhiza pikrias anō phyousa enochlē kai dia tautēs mianthōsin polloi',
   '''Looking diligently'' (episkopountes — overseeing, watching over; from episkopos = bishop/overseer). This is mutual oversight — believers watching out for one another. ''Fail of the grace of God'' (hysterōn apo tēs charitos — falling short of, coming behind God''s grace). ''Root of bitterness'' (rhiza pikrias — echoes Deut 29:18 LXX). A single bitter, unbelieving person can contaminate an entire community. ''Thereby many be defiled'' (mianthōsin polloi — many be polluted). Sin is contagious; apostasy spreads.',
   NULL),
  (16, 'Lest there be any fornicator, or profane person, as Esau, who for one morsel of meat sold his birthright.',
   'μή τις πόρνος ἢ βέβηλος ὡς Ἠσαῦ ὃς ἀντὶ βρώσεως μιᾶς ἀπέδοτο τὰ πρωτοτόκια αὐτοῦ',
   'mē tis pornos ē bebēlos hōs Ēsau hos anti brōseōs mias apedoto ta prōtotokia autou',
   '''Fornicator'' (pornos — sexually immoral). ''Profane person'' (bebēlos — godless, irreverent, treating sacred things as common; from bēlos = threshold — one who crosses sacred thresholds carelessly). Esau is the archetype of the bebēlos: he treated his birthright (prōtotokia — firstborn inheritance) as worthless, trading eternal privilege for momentary appetite. ''One morsel of meat'' (brōseōs mias — a single meal; Gen 25:29-34). The application to the readers is pointed: do not trade your heavenly inheritance for temporary relief from persecution.',
   NULL),
  (17, 'For ye know how that afterward, when he would have inherited the blessing, he was rejected: for he found no place of repentance, though he sought it carefully with tears.',
   'ἴστε γὰρ ὅτι καὶ μετέπειτα θέλων κληρονομῆσαι τὴν εὐλογίαν ἀπεδοκιμάσθη μετανοίας γὰρ τόπον οὐχ εὗρεν καίπερ μετὰ δακρύων ἐκζητήσας αὐτήν',
   'iste gar hoti kai metapeita thelōn klēronomēsai tēn eulogian apedokimasthē metanoias gar topon ouch heuren kaiper meta dakryōn ekzētēsas autēn',
   '''Afterward'' (metapeita — later, subsequently). ''Would have inherited the blessing'' (thelōn klēronomēsai tēn eulogian — wanting to inherit the blessing). ''Was rejected'' (apedokimasthē — was repudiated, found unworthy after testing). ''Found no place of repentance'' (metanoias topon ouch heuren — he found no way to change the outcome). ''Though he sought it carefully with tears'' (kaiper meta dakryōn ekzētēsas — although he searched earnestly with tears). Esau''s tears were not repentance for sin but regret over lost blessing. He wanted the consequences reversed without the character change. This parallels the warning of 6:4-6.',
   'Esau illustrates the danger of passing a point of no return — not because God refuses to forgive the truly repentant, but because certain choices so harden the heart that genuine repentance becomes impossible. The ''place of repentance'' (topon metanoias) he could not find was not God''s willingness but his own ability to truly change. This is the fifth echo of the warning passages (2:1-4, 3:7-4:13, 6:4-8, 10:26-31) that form the backbone of Hebrews.'),
  (18, 'For ye are not come unto the mount that might be touched, and that burned with fire, nor unto blackness, and darkness, and tempest,',
   'οὐ γὰρ προσεληλύθατε ψηλαφωμένῳ ὄρει καὶ κεκαυμένῳ πυρὶ καὶ γνόφῳ καὶ σκότῳ καὶ θυέλλῃ',
   'ou gar proselēlythate psēlaphōmenō orei kai kekaumenō pyri kai gnophō kai skotō kai thuellē',
   '''Ye are not come'' (ou proselēlythate — you have not approached; perfect tense: you have not come and do not stand at). ''The mount that might be touched'' (psēlaphōmenō orei — a tangible, physical mountain — Mount Sinai). ''Burned with fire'' (kekaumenō pyri — ablaze with fire; Exod 19:18). ''Blackness, darkness, tempest'' (gnophō, skotō, thuellē — deep gloom, darkness, storm). The terrifying theophany of Sinai is contrasted with the glorious assembly of Zion. The old covenant was characterized by unapproachable terror.',
   NULL),
  (19, 'And the sound of a trumpet, and the voice of words; which voice they that heard intreated that the word should not be spoken to them any more:',
   'καὶ σάλπιγγος ἤχῳ καὶ φωνῇ ῥημάτων ἧς οἱ ἀκούσαντες παρῃτήσαντο μὴ προστεθῆναι αὐτοῖς λόγον',
   'kai salpingos ēchō kai phōnē rhēmatōn hēs hoi akousantes parētēsanto mē prostethēnai autois logon',
   '''Sound of a trumpet'' (salpingos ēchō — the blast of the shofar; Exod 19:16,19). ''The voice of words'' (phōnē rhēmatōn — the spoken voice of God giving the commandments). ''They that heard intreated that the word should not be spoken'' (parētēsanto mē prostethēnai — they begged that no further word be added; Exod 20:19, Deut 5:25). Israel could not bear the direct voice of God — they asked for a mediator. The old covenant was so terrifying that even God''s people could not endure it.',
   NULL),
  (20, '(For they could not endure that which was commanded, And if so much as a beast touch the mountain, it shall be stoned, or thrust through with a dart:',
   'οὐκ ἔφερον γὰρ τὸ διαστελλόμενον κἂν θηρίον θίγῃ τοῦ ὄρους λιθοβοληθήσεται ἢ βολίδι κατατοξευθήσεται',
   'ouk epheron gar to diastellomenon kan thērion thigē tou orous lithobolēthēsetai ē bolidi katatoxeuthēsetai',
   '''Could not endure'' (ouk epheron — they could not bear). ''That which was commanded'' (to diastellomenon — the command being given). ''If so much as a beast touch the mountain'' (kan thērion thigē tou orous — even if an animal touches the mountain; Exod 19:12-13). ''It shall be stoned'' (lithobolēthēsetai — it shall be pelted with stones). The holiness of Sinai was so terrible that even accidental contact by an animal meant death. This barrier between God and His people is precisely what the new covenant abolishes.',
   NULL),
  (21, 'And so terrible was the sight, that Moses said, I exceedingly fear and quake:)',
   'καὶ οὕτω φοβερὸν ἦν τὸ φανταζόμενον Μωϋσῆς εἶπεν Ἔκφοβός εἰμι καὶ ἔντρομος',
   'kai houtō phoberon ēn to phantazomenon Mōusēs eipen ekphobos eimi kai entromos',
   '''So terrible was the sight'' (houtō phoberon ēn to phantazomenon — so fearful was the spectacle/apparition). Even Moses, the mediator of the old covenant, said ''I exceedingly fear and quake'' (ekphobos eimi kai entromos — I am terrified and trembling; cf. Deut 9:19). If the greatest prophet of the old covenant trembled before Sinai, how much greater is the access believers now have through Christ. The parenthetical vv.18-21 paint the darkest possible picture of Sinai to heighten the contrast with Zion.',
   NULL),
  (22, 'But ye are come unto mount Sion, and unto the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem, and to an innumerable company of angels,',
   'ἀλλὰ προσεληλύθατε Σιὼν ὄρει καὶ πόλει θεοῦ ζῶντος Ἰερουσαλὴμ ἐπουρανίῳ καὶ μυριάσιν ἀγγέλων',
   'alla proselēlythate Siōn orei kai polei theou zōntos Ierousalēm epouraniō kai myriasin angelōn',
   '''But ye are come'' (alla proselēlythate — but you have approached, you have drawn near; same verb as v.18 but now in the positive). Seven glorious realities replace the seven terrors of Sinai: (1) ''Mount Sion'' (Siōn orei — the heavenly Zion, not earthly Jerusalem); (2) ''the city of the living God'' (polei theou zōntos — God''s own city); (3) ''the heavenly Jerusalem'' (Ierousalēm epouraniō — the Jerusalem above, cf. Gal 4:26, Rev 21). (4) ''Innumerable company of angels'' (myriasin angelōn — myriads of angels in festal gathering). The perfect tense is remarkable: believers have already arrived at heavenly Zion.',
   'This is one of the most glorious passages in the NT. Believers under the new covenant have not come to a terrifying mountain of unapproachable holiness but to a heavenly city of joyful assembly. The perfect tense (proselēlythate — ''you have come and stand there now'') means this is a present reality, not merely a future hope. Through Christ, believers already participate in the heavenly Jerusalem.'),
  (23, 'To the general assembly and church of the firstborn, which are written in heaven, and to God the Judge of all, and to the spirits of just men made perfect,',
   'πανηγύρει καὶ ἐκκλησίᾳ πρωτοτόκων ἐν οὐρανοῖς ἀπογεγραμμένων καὶ κριτῇ θεῷ πάντων καὶ πνεύμασιν δικαίων τετελειωμένων',
   'panēgyrei kai ekklēsia prōtotokōn en ouranois apogegrammenōn kai kritē theō pantōn kai pneumasin dikaiōn teteleiōmenōn',
   'Continues the seven realities: (5) ''the general assembly and church of the firstborn'' (panēgyrei kai ekklēsia prōtotokōn — the festal gathering and assembly of the firstborn ones). Panēgyris means a celebratory assembly, a feast; ekklēsia is the called-out assembly. ''Written in heaven'' (en ouranois apogegrammenōn — enrolled, registered in heaven; their names are in the Book of Life). (6) ''God the Judge of all'' (kritē theō pantōn — unlike Sinai where God''s judgment brought terror, here He is approached with confidence). (7) ''The spirits of just men made perfect'' (pneumasin dikaiōn teteleiōmenōn — the OT saints who have been perfected through Christ; cf. 11:39-40).',
   'The ''church of the firstborn'' (ekklēsia prōtotokōn — plural, not singular) identifies all believers as firstborn sons, sharing in Christ''s firstborn status (1:6) and its inheritance rights. ''Just men made perfect'' (dikaiōn teteleiōmenōn) refers to OT saints who, having died in faith without receiving the promise (11:39), have now been perfected through Christ''s once-for-all sacrifice. The old and new covenant people of God are united in this heavenly assembly.'),
  (24, 'And to Jesus the mediator of the new covenant, and to the blood of sprinkling, that speaketh better things than that of Abel.',
   'καὶ διαθήκης νέας μεσίτῃ Ἰησοῦ καὶ αἵματι ῥαντισμοῦ κρεῖττον λαλοῦντι παρὰ τὸν Ἅβελ',
   'kai diathēkēs neas mesitē Iēsou kai haimati rhantismou kreitton lalounti para ton Habel',
   'The climax of the seven realities: ''Jesus the mediator of the new covenant'' (diathēkēs neas mesitē Iēsou — Jesus the go-between of the fresh/new covenant; neas = new in quality, not merely recent). ''The blood of sprinkling'' (haimati rhantismou — the sprinkled blood that inaugurates and seals the covenant; cf. 9:19-22). ''Speaketh better things than that of Abel'' (kreitton lalounti para ton Habel — speaking something superior to Abel''s blood). Abel''s blood cried out for vengeance (Gen 4:10); Christ''s blood speaks forgiveness. Abel''s blood condemned; Christ''s blood redeems.',
   'The contrast between Abel''s blood and Christ''s blood encapsulates the difference between the old and new covenants. Abel''s blood cried ''guilty'' from the ground; Christ''s blood declares ''pardoned'' from heaven. Jesus as ''mediator'' (mesitēs) stands between God and humanity, making the new covenant operative. The ''blood of sprinkling'' recalls both the Passover lamb and the Day of Atonement — Christ''s blood accomplishes what all those types prefigured.'),
  (25, 'See that ye refuse not him that speaketh. For if they escaped not who refused him that spake on earth, much more shall not we escape, if we turn away from him that speaketh from heaven:',
   'βλέπετε μὴ παραιτήσησθε τὸν λαλοῦντα εἰ γὰρ ἐκεῖνοι οὐκ ἔφυγον τὸν ἐπὶ γῆς παραιτησάμενοι χρηματίζοντα πολλῷ μᾶλλον ἡμεῖς οἱ τὸν ἀπ᾽ οὐρανῶν ἀποστρεφόμενοι',
   'blepete mē paraitēsēsthe ton lalounta ei gar ekeinoi ouk ephygon ton epi gēs paraitēsamenoi chrēmatizonta pollō mallon hēmeis hoi ton ap ouranōn apostrephomenoi',
   '''See that ye refuse not'' (blepete mē paraitēsēsthe — beware that you do not reject). The fifth and final warning passage begins. ''Him that speaketh'' (ton lalounta — the one speaking; God/Christ). The a fortiori argument: if Israel ''escaped not'' (ouk ephygon — did not escape judgment) when they refused God speaking ''on earth'' at Sinai, ''much more'' (pollō mallon — by how much more) will judgment fall on those who ''turn away'' (apostrephomenoi — turn their back on) the One speaking ''from heaven.'' Greater revelation brings greater responsibility.',
   'This is the fifth and climactic warning passage in Hebrews (cf. 2:1-4, 3:7-4:13, 6:4-8, 10:26-31). Each warning intensifies: drifting (2:1), hardening (3:8), falling away (6:6), willful sinning (10:26), and now refusing the heavenly voice (12:25). The structure is identical to 2:2-3: if the old covenant brought judgment for disobedience, how much more the new covenant? Greater privilege means greater danger.'),
  (26, 'Whose voice then shook the earth: but now he hath promised, saying, Yet once more I shake not the earth only, but also heaven.',
   'οὗ ἡ φωνὴ τὴν γῆν ἐσάλευσεν τότε νῦν δὲ ἐπήγγελται λέγων Ἔτι ἅπαξ ἐγὼ σείω οὐ μόνον τὴν γῆν ἀλλὰ καὶ τὸν οὐρανόν',
   'hou hē phōnē tēn gēn esaleusen tote nyn de epēngeltai legōn eti hapax egō seiō ou monon tēn gēn alla kai ton ouranon',
   '''Whose voice then shook the earth'' (hē phōnē tēn gēn esaleusen — His voice shook the earth at Sinai; Exod 19:18). Quotes Haggai 2:6: ''Yet once more'' (eti hapax — one final time). ''I shake not the earth only, but also heaven'' (seiō ou monon tēn gēn alla kai ton ouranon). The first shaking was at Sinai (earth only); the final shaking will include heaven and earth. God will shake everything shakeable, leaving only what is eternal and unshakeable.',
   NULL),
  (27, 'And this word, Yet once more, signifieth the removing of those things that are shaken, as of things that are made, that those things which cannot be shaken may remain.',
   'τὸ δὲ Ἔτι ἅπαξ δηλοῖ τῶν σαλευομένων τὴν μετάθεσιν ὡς πεποιημένων ἵνα μείνῃ τὰ μὴ σαλευόμενα',
   'to de eti hapax dēloi tōn saleuomenōn tēn metathesin hōs pepoiēmenōn hina meinē ta mē saleuomena',
   '''Signifieth'' (dēloi — makes clear, indicates). ''The removing of those things that are shaken'' (tōn saleuomenōn tēn metathesin — the transference/removal of the shakeable things). ''As of things that are made'' (hōs pepoiēmenōn — as created things, temporary things). ''That those things which cannot be shaken may remain'' (hina meinē ta mē saleuomena — so that the unshakeable things may abide). The old covenant, the old creation, all temporal structures will be removed. Only what belongs to God''s eternal kingdom — the new covenant realities of vv.22-24 — will remain.',
   'The eschatological shaking separates the temporal from the eternal. Everything ''made'' (pepoiēmenōn — manufactured, created, belonging to the old order) will be removed. What remains is the ''kingdom which cannot be moved'' (v.28) — the new covenant community, the heavenly Jerusalem, the mediatorial work of Christ. This is both a comfort (our inheritance is unshakeable) and a warning (everything else will be stripped away).'),
  (28, 'Wherefore we receiving a kingdom which cannot be moved, let us have grace, whereby we may serve God acceptably with reverence and godly fear:',
   'διὸ βασιλείαν ἀσάλευτον παραλαμβάνοντες ἔχωμεν χάριν δι᾽ ἧς λατρεύωμεν εὐαρέστως τῷ θεῷ μετὰ αἰδοῦς καὶ εὐλαβείας',
   'dio basileian asaleuton paralambanontes echōmen charin di hēs latreuōmen euarestōs tō theō meta aidous kai eulabeias',
   '''A kingdom which cannot be moved'' (basileian asaleuton — an unshakeable kingdom; the only permanent reality in a world being shaken). ''Let us have grace'' (echōmen charin — let us hold fast to grace, or let us be thankful; both meanings are present). ''Serve God acceptably'' (latreuōmen euarestōs tō theō — worship God in a way that pleases Him; latreuō = priestly service). ''With reverence and godly fear'' (meta aidous kai eulabeias — with awe/modesty and godly caution/reverence). Grace does not abolish reverence; it transforms it from terror (Sinai) to godly awe (Zion).',
   'The unshakeable kingdom is the present possession of believers — not a distant future. The proper response to receiving it is grace-empowered worship with appropriate reverence. Reverence (aidōs) and godly fear (eulabeia) are not the terror of Sinai but the holy awe of those who have been brought near to the living God. The new covenant does not make God less holy; it makes access possible through the blood of Christ.'),
  (29, 'For our God is a consuming fire.',
   'καὶ γὰρ ὁ θεὸς ἡμῶν πῦρ καταναλίσκον',
   'kai gar ho theos hēmōn pyr katanaliskon',
   'Quotes Deuteronomy 4:24. ''Our God'' (ho theos hēmōn — the God who belongs to us and to whom we belong). ''A consuming fire'' (pyr katanaliskon — a fire that consumes, devours completely). This is not the fire of Sinai that terrified from a distance but the fire of divine holiness that burns up everything unworthy. The closing phrase of the chapter is deliberately shocking: the God of grace, the God of the new covenant, the God who invites us to heavenly Zion — is still a consuming fire. Grace does not diminish God''s holiness; it provides the means to stand before it.',
   'The final verse anchors the entire chapter: the God of the unshakeable kingdom, the God of Mount Zion, the God of the new covenant — is the same God who descended on Sinai in fire. He has not changed. What has changed is our access to Him through Christ. The consuming fire that would have destroyed sinners at Sinai now purifies and refines believers in Zion. This verse prevents any presumption: the grace of the new covenant is not license but the means of holy approach to a holy God.')
) AS v(verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
WHERE b.name = 'Hebrews' AND c.chapter_number = 12;

-- Step 3: Insert word studies (6 key Greek terms)
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, w.original_word, w.transliteration, w.strongs_number, w.meaning, w.word_order
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  ('ὑπομονή', 'hypomonē', 'G5281',
   'Patient endurance, steadfast perseverance, remaining under pressure — from hypo (under) + menō (to remain, to abide). Not passive resignation but active, resolute endurance that keeps running when every fiber says to stop. The great virtue of the Christian race: not speed but endurance. Used throughout Hebrews for the quality that enabled the chapter 11 heroes to persevere.', 1),
  ('ἀρχηγός', 'archēgos', 'G747',
   'Author, pioneer, originator, trail-blazer, captain — from archē (beginning) + agō (to lead). Christ is the archēgos of faith: He went first, blazed the trail, and enables others to follow. Also used in 2:10 (captain of their salvation) and Acts 3:15 (Prince of life). Jesus is not merely a faith-teacher but the one who originates, demonstrates, and perfects faith by running the race first.', 2),
  ('τελειωτής', 'teleiōtēs', 'G5051',
   'Perfecter, finisher, completer — from teleioō (to bring to completion, to perfect). This word occurs only here in the entire NT. Christ is both the originator (archēgos) and perfecter (teleiōtēs) of faith — He begins it and brings it to completion. The concept is not that Jesus had faith that we should imitate, but that He pioneered and perfected the entire enterprise of faith.', 3),
  ('παιδεία', 'paideia', 'G3809',
   'Discipline, training, education, instruction, correction — from pais (child). The central concept of vv.5-11: God''s fatherly discipline of His children. In classical Greek, paideia was the comprehensive education and formation of a child into a mature citizen. In Hebrews, it encompasses everything God uses to train His children: trials, suffering, correction, and hardship — all aimed at producing the ''peaceable fruit of righteousness'' (v.11).', 4),
  ('ἀσάλευτος', 'asaleutos', 'G761',
   'Unshakeable, immovable, that which cannot be shaken — from a (negative) + saleuō (to shake, to agitate). Describes the kingdom believers have received (v.28). While everything in the created order will be shaken and removed, the kingdom of God — the new covenant realities — will remain forever. This is the eschatological hope: belonging to something permanent in a world of impermanence.', 5),
  ('μεσίτης', 'mesitēs', 'G3316',
   'Mediator, go-between, intermediary — from mesos (middle). Jesus is the mediator of the new covenant (v.24, cf. 8:6, 9:15). A mediator stands between two parties to bring them together. Christ mediates between God and humanity: His blood speaks better things than Abel''s blood (v.24), making reconciliation possible where Sinai''s terrors made approach impossible.', 6)
) AS ws(original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'Hebrews' AND c.chapter_number = 12
AND v.verse_number = CASE ws.word_order
  WHEN 1 THEN 1
  WHEN 2 THEN 2
  WHEN 3 THEN 2
  WHEN 4 THEN 5
  WHEN 5 THEN 28
  WHEN 6 THEN 24
END;

